[src:scikit-image/auto-examples-index] A gallery of examples and that showcase how scikit-image can be used.
[src:scikit-image/auto-examples-index] Some examples demonstrate the use of the API in general and some demonstrate specific applications in tutorial form.
[src:scikit-image/auto-examples-index] Check out our User guide for a narrative introduction to key library conventions and basic image manipulation.
[src:scikit-image/auto-examples-index] In this folder, we have examples for advanced topics, including detailed explanations of the inner workings of certain algorithms.
[src:scikit-image/auto-examples-index] These examples require some basic knowledge of image processing.
[src:scikit-image/auto-examples-index] They are targeted at existing or would-be scikit-image developers wishing to develop their knowledge of image processing algorithms.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] A corner can be defined as the intersection of two edges.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] A corner can also be defined as a point for which there are two dominant and different edge directions in a local neighbourhood of the point.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] An interest point is a point in an image which has a well-defined position and can be robustly detected.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] This means that an interest point can be a corner but it can also be, for example, an isolated point of local intensity maximum or minimum, line endings, or a point on a curve where the curvature is locally maximal.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] In practice, most so-called corner detection methods detect interest points in general, and in fact, the term "corner" and "interest point" are used more or less interchangeably through the literature.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] As a consequence, if only corners are to be detected it is necessary to do a local analysis of detected interest points to determine which of these are real corners.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Examples of edge detection that can be used with post-processing to detect corners are the Kirsch operator and the Frei-Chen masking set.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] "Corner", "interest point" and "feature" are used interchangeably in literature, confusing the issue.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Specifically, there are several blob detectors that can be referred to as "interest point operators", but which are sometimes erroneously referred to as "corner detectors".
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Moreover, there exists a notion of ridge detection to capture the presence of elongated objects.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Corner detectors are not usually very robust and often require large redundancies introduced to prevent the effect of individual errors from dominating the recognition task.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] One determination of the quality of a corner detector is its ability to detect the same corner in multiple similar images, under conditions of different lighting, translation, rotation and other transforms.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] A simple approach to corner detection in images is using correlation, but this gets very computationally expensive and suboptimal.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] An alternative approach used frequently is based on a method proposed by Harris and Stephens (below), which in turn is an improvement of a method by Moravec.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] This is one of the earliest corner detection algorithms and defines a *corner* to be a point with low self-similarity.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The algorithm tests each pixel in the image to see whether a corner is present by considering how similar a patch centered on the pixel is to nearby, largely overlapping patches.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The similarity is measured by taking the sum of squared differences (SSD) between the corresponding pixels of two patches.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] A lower number indicates more similarity.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If the pixel is in a region of uniform intensity, then the nearby patches will look similar.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If the pixel is on an edge, then nearby patches in a direction perpendicular to the edge will look quite different, but nearby patches in a direction parallel to the edge will result in only a small change.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If the pixel is on a feature with variation in all directions, then none of the nearby patches will look similar.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The corner strength is defined as the smallest SSD between the patch and its neighbours (horizontal, vertical and on the two diagonals).
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The reason is that if this number is high, then the variation along all shifts is either equal to it or larger than it, so capturing that all nearby patches look different.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If the corner strength number is computed for all locations, that it is locally maximal for one location indicates that a feature of interest is present in it.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Harris and Stephens improved upon Moravec's corner detector by considering the differential of the corner score with respect to direction directly, instead of using shifted patches.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] (This corner score is often referred to as autocorrelation, since the term is used in the paper in which this detector is described.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Without loss of generality, we will assume a grayscale 2-dimensional image is used.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Consider taking an image patch over the area $(u,v)$ and shifting it by $(x,y)$ .
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The weighted *sum of squared differences* (SSD) between these two patches, denoted S , is given by $S(x,y)=\sum _{u}\sum _{v}w(u,v)[I(u+x,v+y)-I(u,v)]^{2}.$ $I(u+x,v+y)$ can be approximated by a Taylor expansion.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] In words, we find the covariance of the partial derivative of the image intensity I with respect to the x and y axes.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Angle brackets denote averaging (i.e. summation over $(u,v)$ ), and $w(u,v)$ denotes the type of window that slides over the image.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If a box filter is used, the response will be anisotropic, but if a Gaussian is used, then the response will be isotropic.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] A corner (or in general an interest point) is characterized by a large variation of S in all directions of the vector ${\begin{bmatrix}x&y\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] By analyzing the eigenvalues of A , this characterization can be expressed in the following way: A should have two "large" eigenvalues for an interest point.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If $\lambda _{1}\approx 0$ and $\lambda _{2}$ has some large positive value, then an edge is found.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If $\lambda _{1}$ and $\lambda _{2}$ have large positive values, then a corner is found.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Therefore, the algorithm does not have to actually compute the eigenvalue decomposition of the matrix $A,$ and instead it is sufficient to evaluate the determinant and trace of A to find corners, or rather interest points in general.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The Shi–Tomasi corner detector directly computes $\min(\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2})$ because under certain assumptions, the corners are more stable for tracking.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Note that this method is also sometimes referred to as the Kanade–Tomasi corner detector.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The value of $\kappa$ has to be determined empirically, and in the literature values in the range 0.04–0.15 have been reported as feasible.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] One can avoid setting the parameter $\kappa$ by using Noble's corner measure $M_{c}'$ which amounts to the harmonic mean of the eigenvalues: $M_{c}'=2{\frac {\det(A)}{\operatorname {tr} (A)+\epsilon }},$ where $\epsilon$ is a small positive constant.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] In some cases, one may wish to compute the location of a corner with subpixel accuracy.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] To achieve an approximate solution, the Förstner algorithm solves for the point closest to all the tangent lines of the corner in a given window and is a least-square solution.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The algorithm relies on the fact that for an ideal corner, tangent lines cross at a single point.
