[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] SUSAN is an acronym standing for *smallest univalue segment assimilating nucleus*.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] This method is the subject of a 1994 UK patent which is no longer in force.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] For feature detection, SUSAN places a circular mask over the pixel to be tested (the nucleus).
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The region of the mask is M , and a pixel in this mask is represented by ${\vec {m}}\in M$ .
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] where t is the brightness difference threshold, I is the brightness of the pixel and the power of the exponent has been determined empirically.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] This function has the appearance of a smoothed top-hat or rectangular function.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If c is the rectangular function, then n is the number of pixels in the mask which are within t of the nucleus.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] where g is named the 'geometric threshold'.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] In other words, the SUSAN operator only has a positive score if the area is small enough.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The smallest SUSAN locally can be found using non-maximal suppression, and this is the complete SUSAN operator.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The value t determines how similar points have to be to the nucleus before they are considered to be part of the univalue segment.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The value of g determines the minimum size of the univalue segment.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If g is large enough, then this becomes an edge detector.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] For corner detection, two further steps are used.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Firstly, the centroid of the SUSAN is found.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] A proper corner will have the centroid far from the nucleus.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The second step insists that all points on the line from the nucleus through the centroid out to the edge of the mask are in the SUSAN.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] In a manner similar to SUSAN, this detector directly tests whether a patch under a pixel is self-similar by examining nearby pixels. ${\vec {c}}$ is the pixel to be considered, and ${\vec {p}}\in P$ is point on a circle P centered around ${\vec {c}}$ .
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The point ${\vec {p}}'$ is the point opposite to ${\vec {p}}$ along the diameter.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] This will be large when there is no direction in which the centre pixel is similar to two nearby pixels along a diameter.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] P is a discretised circle (a Bresenham circle), so interpolation is used for intermediate diameters to give a more isotropic response.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Since any computation gives an upper bound on the $\min$ , the horizontal and vertical directions are checked first to see if it is worth proceeding with the complete computation of c .
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] AST is an acronym standing for *accelerated segment test*.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] This test is a relaxed version of the SUSAN corner criterion.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Instead of evaluating the circular disc, only the pixels in a Bresenham circle of radius r around the candidate point are considered.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] If n contiguous pixels are all brighter than the nucleus by at least t or all darker than the nucleus by t , then the pixel under the nucleus is considered to be a feature.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] This test is reported to produce very stable features.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The choice of the order in which the pixels are tested is a so-called Twenty Questions problem.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Building short decision trees for this problem results in the most computationally efficient feature detectors available.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The first corner detection algorithm based on the AST is FAST (features from accelerated segment test).
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Although r can in principle take any value, FAST uses only a value of 3 (corresponding to a circle of 16 pixels circumference), and tests show that the best results are achieved with n being 9.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] This value of n is the lowest one at which edges are not detected.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] The order in which pixels are tested is determined by the ID3 algorithm from a training set of images.
[src:scikit-image/corner-detection] Confusingly, the name of the detector is somewhat similar to the name of the paper describing Trajkovic and Hedley's detector.
