[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The purpose of detecting sharp changes in image brightness is to capture important events and changes in properties of the world.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] In the ideal case, the result of applying an edge detector to an image may lead to a set of connected curves that indicate the boundaries of objects, the boundaries of surface markings as well as curves that correspond to discontinuities in surface orientation.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Thus, applying an edge detection algorithm to an image may significantly reduce the amount of data to be processed and may therefore filter out information that may be regarded as less relevant, while preserving the important structural properties of an image.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] If the edge detection step is successful, the subsequent task of interpreting the information contents in the original image may therefore be substantially simplified.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] However, it is not always possible to obtain such ideal edges from real life images of moderate complexity.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Edge detection is one of the fundamental steps in image processing, image analysis, image pattern recognition, and computer vision techniques.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The edges extracted from a two-dimensional image of a three-dimensional scene can be classified as either viewpoint dependent or viewpoint independent.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] A *viewpoint independent edge* typically reflects inherent properties of the three-dimensional objects, such as surface markings and surface shape.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] A *viewpoint dependent edge* may change as the viewpoint changes, and typically reflects the geometry of the scene, such as objects occluding one another.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] A typical edge might for instance be the border between a block of red color and a block of yellow.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] In contrast a **line** (as can be extracted by a ridge detector) can be a small number of pixels of a different color on an otherwise unchanging background.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] For a line, there may therefore usually be one edge on each side of the line.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Although certain literature has considered the detection of ideal step edges, the edges obtained from natural images are usually not at all ideal step edges.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] A number of researchers have used a Gaussian smoothed step edge (an error function) as the simplest extension of the ideal step edge model for modeling the effects of edge blur in practical applications.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] At the left side of the edge, the intensity is $I_{\ell }=\lim _{x\rightarrow -\infty }f(x)$ , and right of the edge it is $I_{r}=\lim _{x\rightarrow \infty }f(x)$ .
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The scale parameter $\sigma$ is called the blur scale of the edge.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Ideally this scale parameter should be adjusted based on the quality of image to avoid destroying true edges of the image.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Outside of images with simple objects or featuring well-controlled lighting, edge detection is not a trivial task, since it can be difficult to determine what threshold should be used to define an edge between two pixels.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] However, if the intensity difference between the 4th and the 5th pixels were smaller, it would not be as easy to say that there should be an edge in the corresponding region.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Similarly, if the intensity differences between the adjacent neighboring pixels were higher, one could argue that more than one edge should be considered to exist, or even none at all.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] There are many methods for edge detection, but most of them can be grouped into two categories, search-based and zero-crossing based.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The zero-crossing based methods search for zero crossings in a second-order derivative expression computed from the image in order to find edges, usually the zero-crossings of the Laplacian or the zero-crossings of a non-linear differential expression.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] As a pre-processing step to edge detection, a smoothing stage, typically Gaussian smoothing, is almost always applied (see also noise reduction).
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The edge detection methods that have been published mainly differ in the types of smoothing filters that are applied and the way the measures of edge strength are computed.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] As many edge detection methods rely on the computation of image gradients, they also differ in the types of filters used for computing gradient estimates in the *x*- and *y*-directions.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] A survey of a number of different edge detection methods can be found in (Ziou and Tabbone 1998); see also the encyclopedia articles on edge detection in *Encyclopedia of Mathematics* and Encyclopedia of Computer Science and Engineering.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] John Canny considered the mathematical problem of deriving an optimal smoothing filter, given the criteria of detection, localization and minimizing multiple responses to a single edge.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] He showed that the optimal filter, given these assumptions, is a sum of four exponential terms.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] He also showed that this filter can be well approximated by first-order derivatives of Gaussians.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Canny also introduced the notion of non-maximum suppression, which means that, given the presmoothing filters, edge points are defined as points where the gradient magnitude assumes a local maximum in the gradient direction.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Looking for the zero crossing of the 2nd derivative along the gradient direction was first proposed by Haralick.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] It took less than two decades to find a modern geometric variational meaning for that operator, that links it to the Marr–Hildreth (zero crossing of the Laplacian) edge detector.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] That observation was presented by Ron Kimmel and Alfred Bruckstein.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Although his work was done in the early days of computer vision, the Canny edge detector (including its variations) is still a state-of-the-art edge detector.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Edge detectors that perform better than the Canny usually require longer computation times or a greater number of parameters.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Kovalevsky has suggested a quite different approach.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] He uses a preprocessing of the image with the Sigma filter and with a special filter for the dilution of the ramps.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] This method uses no brightness of the image but only the intensities of the color channels which is important for detecting an edge between two adjacent pixels of equal brightness but different colors.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The method scans the image two times: first along the horizontal lines and second along the vertical columns.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] In each horizontal line six consequent adjacent pixels are considered and five color difference between each two adjacent pixels are calculated.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Each color difference is the sum of absolute differences of the intensities of the color channels Red, Green, and Blue of the corresponding adjacent pixels.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] If this sum is greater than a given threshold, then the sign of the color difference is set equal to the sign of the difference of the green intensities.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] If the green difference is zero, then the sign of the color difference is set equal to the sign of the difference of the red intensities.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] If, however, both the green and the red differences are zero, then the sign of the color difference is set equal to the sign of the blue difference which in this case cannot be zero since the sum is greater than the threshold.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Certain conditions for the values and signs of the five color differences are specified in such way that if the conditions are fulfilled, then a short vertical stroke is put between the third and the fourth of the six pixels as the label of the edge.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Similar calculations are performed for the vertical columns.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] In this case a short horizontal stroke is put between the third and the fourth of the six subsequent pixels.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The vertical and horizontal strokes (being the one-dimensional cells of an abstract cell complex corresponding to the image) mostly compose a connected sequence representing the edge.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] This method is robust and very fast and, what is more important, it can detect edges between adjacent pixels of equal brightness’s if the color difference between these pixels is greater than the threshold.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The Canny–Deriche detector was derived from similar mathematical criteria as the Canny edge detector, although starting from a discrete viewpoint and then leading to a set of recursive filters for image smoothing instead of exponential filters or Gaussian filters.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The differential edge detector described below can be seen as a reformulation of Canny's method from the viewpoint of differential invariants computed from a scale space representation leading to a number of advantages in terms of both theoretical analysis and sub-pixel implementation.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] In that aspect, Log Gabor filter have been shown to be a good choice to extract boundaries in natural scenes.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Different gradient operators can be applied to estimate image gradients from the input image or a smoothed version of it.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Other first-order difference operators for estimating image gradient have been proposed in the Prewitt operator, Roberts cross, Kayyali operator and Frei–Chen operator.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] It is possible to extend filters dimension to avoid the issue of recognizing edge in low SNR image.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The cost of this operation is loss in terms of resolution.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Once we have computed a measure of edge strength (typically the gradient magnitude), the next stage is to apply a threshold, to decide whether edges are present or not at an image point.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The lower the threshold, the more edges will be detected, and the result will be increasingly susceptible to noise and detecting edges of irrelevant features in the image.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Conversely a high threshold may miss subtle edges, or result in fragmented edges.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] If the edge is applied to just the gradient magnitude image, the resulting edges will in general be thick and some type of edge thinning post-processing is necessary.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] For edges detected with non-maximum suppression however, the edge curves are thin by definition and the edge pixels can be linked into edge polygon by an edge linking (edge tracking) procedure.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] A commonly used approach to handle the problem of appropriate thresholds for thresholding is by using thresholding with hysteresis.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] This method uses multiple thresholds to find edges.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] We begin by using the upper threshold to find the start of an edge.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Once we have a start point, we then trace the path of the edge through the image pixel by pixel, marking an edge whenever we are above the lower threshold.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] We stop marking our edge only when the value falls below our lower threshold.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] This approach makes the assumption that edges are likely to be in continuous curves, and allows us to follow a faint section of an edge we have previously seen, without meaning that every noisy pixel in the image is marked down as an edge.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Still, however, we have the problem of choosing appropriate thresholding parameters, and suitable thresholding values may vary over the image.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] This method finds connected set of pixels having a directional derivative magnitude larger than a fairly small threshold.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] It considers only presence of gradients instead of strength of gradients.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] After applying a dramatically small threshold (i.e.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The morphological opening operation and the morphological closing operation are applied to the binary image to close gaps.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Then, the distance transform operation is applied to the binary image to clear the pixels far from the background, so blob-like shapes or other false labeled regions are deleted from the edge map.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Edge thinning is a technique used to remove the unwanted spurious points on the edges in an image.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] This technique is employed after the image has been filtered for noise (using median, Gaussian filter etc.), the edge operator has been applied (like the ones described above, Canny or Sobel) to detect the edges and after the edges have been smoothed using an appropriate threshold value.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] This removes all the unwanted points, and if applied carefully, results in one pixel thick edge elements.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] If Hough transforms are used to detect lines and ellipses, then thinning could give much better results.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] If the edge happens to be the boundary of a region, then thinning could easily give the image parameters like perimeter without much algebra.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] 8 connectivity is preferred, where all the immediate pixels surrounding a particular pixel are considered.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Remove points from North, south, east and west.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Do this in multiple passes, i.e. after the north pass, use the same semi processed image in the other passes and so on.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Remove a point if: The point has no neighbors in the North (if you are in the north pass, and respective directions for other passes).
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Removing the points will not cause to disconnect its neighbors in any way.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The number of passes across direction should be chosen according to the level of accuracy desired.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Some edge-detection operators are instead based upon second-order derivatives of the intensity.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] This essentially captures the rate of change in the intensity gradient.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Thus, in the ideal continuous case, detection of zero-crossings in the second derivative captures local maxima in the gradient.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The early Marr–Hildreth operator is based on the detection of zero-crossings of the Laplacian operator applied to a Gaussian-smoothed image.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] It can be shown, however, that this operator will also return false edges corresponding to local minima of the gradient magnitude.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Moreover, this operator will give poor localization at curved edges.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Hence, this operator is today mainly of historical interest.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Following the differential geometric way of expressing the requirement of non-maximum suppression proposed by Lindeberg, let us introduce at every image point a local coordinate system $(u,v)$ , with the v -direction parallel to the gradient direction.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] where $L_{x},L_{y},\ldots ,L_{yyy}$ denote partial derivatives computed from a scale space representation L obtained by smoothing the original image with a Gaussian kernel.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] In this way, the edges will be automatically obtained as continuous curves with sub-pixel accuracy.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Hysteresis thresholding can also be applied to these differential and subpixel edge segments.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Higher-order derivatives for the third-order sign condition can be obtained in an analogous fashion.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] A recent development in edge detection techniques takes a frequency domain approach to finding edge locations.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Phase congruency (also known as phase coherence) methods attempt to find locations in an image where all sinusoids in the frequency domain are in phase.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] These locations will generally correspond to the location of a perceived edge, regardless of whether the edge is represented by a large change in intensity in the spatial domain.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] A key benefit of this technique is that it responds strongly to Mach bands, and avoids false positives typically found around roof edges.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] A roof edge, is a discontinuity in the first order derivative of a grey-level profile.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The phase stretch transform or PST is a physics-inspired computational approach to signal and image processing.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] One of its utilities is for feature detection and classification.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] PST is a spin-off from research on the time stretch dispersive Fourier transform.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] PST transforms the image by emulating propagation through a diffractive medium with engineered 3D dispersive property (refractive index).
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The operation relies on symmetry of the dispersion profile and can be understood in terms of dispersive eigenfunctions or stretch modes.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] PST performs similar functionality as phase contrast microscopy but on digital images.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] PST is also applicable to digital images as well as temporal, time series, data.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] To increase the precision of edge detection, several subpixel techniques had been proposed, including curve-fitting, moment-based, reconstructive, and partial area effect methods.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] These methods have different characteristics.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Curve fitting methods are computationally simple but are easily affected by noise.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Moment-based methods use an integral-based approach to reduce the effect of noise, but may require more computations in some cases.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Reconstructive methods use horizontal gradients or vertical gradients to build a curve and find the peak of the curve as the sub-pixel edge.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Partial area effect methods are based on the hypothesis that each pixel value depends on the area at both sides of the edge inside that pixel, producing accurate individual estimation for every edge pixel.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Certain variants of the moment-based technique have been shown to be the most accurate for isolated edges.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The Marr-Hildreth edge detector is distinguished by its use of the Laplacian of Gaussian (LoG) operator for edge detection in digital images.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Unlike other edge detection methods, the LoG approach combines Gaussian smoothing with second derivative operations, allowing for simultaneous noise reduction and edge enhancement.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] The key advantage of this method lies in its ability to detect edges at various scales by adjusting the standard deviation of the Gaussian kernel, enabling detection of fine details as well as broader transitions.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] Moreover, the technique leverages zero-crossing detection on the LoG response to precisely locate edges, offering robustness against noise and maintaining edge continuity.
[src:scikit-image/edge-detection] This approach is particularly effective for detecting edges with clear boundaries in images while minimizing false positives due to noise, making it a valuable tool in computer vision applications where accurate edge localization is crucial.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Image registration or image alignment algorithms can be classified into intensity-based and feature-based.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] One of the images is referred to as the *target*, *fixed* or *sensed* image and the others are referred to as the *moving* or *source* images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Image registration involves spatially transforming the source/moving image(s) to align with the target image.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] The reference frame in the target image is stationary, while the other datasets are transformed to match to the target.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Intensity-based methods compare intensity patterns in images via correlation metrics, while feature-based methods find correspondence between image features such as points, lines, and contours.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Intensity-based methods register entire images or sub-images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] If sub-images are registered, centers of corresponding sub images are treated as corresponding feature points.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Feature-based methods establish a correspondence between a number of especially distinct points in images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Knowing the correspondence between a number of points in images, a geometrical transformation is then determined to map the target image to the reference images, thereby establishing point-by-point correspondence between the reference and target images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Methods combining intensity-based and feature-based information have also been developed.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Image registration algorithms can also be classified according to the transformation models they use to relate the target image space to the reference image space.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] The first broad category of transformation models includes affine transformations, which include rotation, scaling, translation and shearing.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Affine transformations are global in nature, thus, they cannot model local geometric differences between images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] The second category of transformations allow 'elastic' or 'nonrigid' transformations.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] These transformations are capable of locally warping the target image to align with the reference image.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Nonrigid transformations include radial basis functions (thin-plate or surface splines, multiquadrics, and compactly-supported transformations), physical continuum models (viscous fluids), and large deformation models (diffeomorphisms).
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Transformations are commonly described by a parametrization, where the model dictates the number of parameters.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] For instance, the translation of a full image can be described by a translation vector parameter.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] These models are called parametric models.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Non-parametric models on the other hand, do not follow any parameterization, allowing each image element to be displaced arbitrarily.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] There are a number of programs that implement both estimation and application of a warp-field.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] It is a part of the SPM and AIR programs.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Alternatively, many advanced methods for spatial normalization are building on structure preserving transformations homeomorphisms and diffeomorphisms since they carry smooth submanifolds smoothly during transformation.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Diffeomorphisms are generated in the modern field of Computational Anatomy based on flows since diffeomorphisms are not additive although they form a group, but a group under the law of function composition.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] For this reason, flows which generalize the ideas of additive groups allow for generating large deformations that preserve topology, providing 1-1 and onto transformations.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Computational methods for generating such transformation are often called LDDMM which provide flows of diffeomorphisms as the main computational tool for connecting coordinate systems corresponding to the geodesic flows of Computational Anatomy.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Spatial methods operate in the image domain, matching intensity patterns or features in images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Some of the feature matching algorithms are outgrowths of traditional techniques for performing manual image registration, in which an operator chooses corresponding control points (CP) in images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] When the number of control points exceeds the minimum required to define the appropriate transformation model, iterative algorithms like RANSAC can be used to robustly estimate the parameters of a particular transformation type (e.g. affine) for registration of the images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Frequency-domain methods find the transformation parameters for registration of the images while working in the transform domain.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Such methods work for simple transformations, such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Applying the phase correlation method to a pair of images produces a third image which contains a single peak.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] The location of this peak corresponds to the relative translation between the images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Unlike many spatial-domain algorithms, the phase correlation method is resilient to noise, occlusions, and other defects typical of medical or satellite images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Additionally, the phase correlation uses the fast Fourier transform to compute the cross-correlation between the two images, generally resulting in large performance gains.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] The method can be extended to determine rotation and scaling differences between two images by first converting the images to log-polar coordinates.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Due to properties of the Fourier transform, the rotation and scaling parameters can be determined in a manner invariant to translation.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Another classification can be made between single-modality and multi-modality methods.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Single-modality methods tend to register images in the same modality acquired by the same scanner/sensor type, while multi-modality registration methods tended to register images acquired by different scanner/sensor types.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Multi-modality registration methods are often used in medical imaging as images of a subject are frequently obtained from different scanners.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Registration methods may be classified based on the level of automation they provide.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Manual, interactive, semi-automatic, and automatic methods have been developed.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Manual methods provide tools to align the images manually.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Interactive methods reduce user bias by performing certain key operations automatically while still relying on the user to guide the registration.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Semi-automatic methods perform more of the registration steps automatically but depend on the user to verify the correctness of a registration.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Automatic methods do not allow any user interaction and perform all registration steps automatically.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Image similarities are broadly used in medical imaging.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] An image similarity measure quantifies the degree of similarity between intensity patterns in two images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] The choice of an image similarity measure depends on the modality of the images to be registered.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Common examples of image similarity measures include cross-correlation, mutual information, sum of squared intensity differences, and ratio image uniformity.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Mutual information and normalized mutual information are the most popular image similarity measures for registration of multimodality images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Cross-correlation, sum of squared intensity differences and ratio image uniformity are commonly used for registration of images in the same modality.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] There is a level of uncertainty associated with registering images that have any spatio-temporal differences.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] A confident registration with a measure of uncertainty is critical for many change detection applications such as medical diagnostics.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] In remote sensing applications where a digital image pixel may represent several kilometers of spatial distance (such as NASA's LANDSAT imagery), an uncertain image registration can mean that a solution could be several kilometers from ground truth.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Several notable papers have attempted to quantify uncertainty in image registration in order to compare results.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] However, many approaches to quantifying uncertainty or estimating deformations are computationally intensive or are only applicable to limited sets of spatial transformations.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Image registration has applications in remote sensing (cartography updating), and computer vision.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Due to the vast range of applications to which image registration can be applied, it is impossible to develop a general method that is optimized for all uses.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Nonrigid registration of medical images can also be used to register a patient's data to an anatomical atlas, such as the Talairach atlas for neuroimaging.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Another application of image registration for medical imaging is the registration of a number of subjects to a single reference space for cohort-wise analyses .
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] In other cases, nonrigid registration is explicitly not utilized since rigid registration methods preserve the underlying geometry, e.g., in inner ear imaging.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] This is preferred for structures with low variability in anatomy in the cohort that is being studied.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] In Radiation therapy rigid image registration (RIR) is a fundamental element in most imaging software systems.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] It involves aligning images by applying translational and rotational adjustments, up to a six degrees of freedom—three for translation along the x, y, and z axes, and three for rotation about these axes.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] RIR aligns images appropriately using these six parameters, allowing for precise treatment planning and delivery.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] In astrophotography, image alignment and stacking are often used to increase the signal to noise ratio for faint objects.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Without stacking it may be used to produce a timelapse of events such as a planet's rotation of a transit across the Sun.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Using control points (automatically or manually entered), the computer performs transformations on one image to make major features align with a second or multiple images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] This technique may also be used for images of different sizes, to allow images taken through different telescopes or lenses to be combined.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] In cryo-TEM, instability causes specimen drift and many fast acquisitions with accurate image registration is required to preserve high resolution and obtain high signal to noise images.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] For low SNR data, the best image registration is achieved by cross-correlating all permutations of images in an image stack.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] Image registration is an essential part of panoramic image creation.
[src:scikit-image/image-registration] There are many different techniques that can be implemented in real time and run on embedded devices like cameras and camera-phones.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In digital image processing and computer vision, **image segmentation** is the process of partitioning a digital image into multiple **image segments**, also known as **image regions** or **image objects** (sets of pixels).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The goal of segmentation is to simplify and/or change the representation of an image into something that is more meaningful and easier to analyze.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Image segmentation is typically used to locate objects and boundaries (lines, curves, etc.) in images.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] More precisely, image segmentation is the process of assigning a label to every pixel in an image such that pixels with the same label share certain characteristics.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The result of image segmentation is a set of segments that collectively cover the entire image, or a set of contours extracted from the image (see edge detection).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Each of the pixels in a region are similar with respect to some characteristic or computed property, such as color, intensity, or texture.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Adjacent regions are significantly different with respect to the same characteristic(s).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] When applied to a stack of images, typical in medical imaging, the resulting contours after image segmentation can be used to create 3D reconstructions with the help of geometry reconstruction algorithms like marching cubes.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Several general-purpose algorithms and techniques have been developed for image segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] To be useful, these techniques must typically be combined with a domain's specific knowledge in order to effectively solve the domain's segmentation problems.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] There are two classes of segmentation techniques.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The simplest method of image segmentation is called the thresholding method.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This method is based on a clip-level (or a threshold value) to turn a gray-scale image into a binary image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The key of this method is to select the threshold value (or values when multiple-levels are selected).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Several popular methods are used in industry including the maximum entropy method, balanced histogram thresholding, Otsu's method (maximum variance), and k-means clustering.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Recently, methods have been developed for thresholding computed tomography (CT) images.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The key idea is that, unlike Otsu's method, the thresholds are derived from the radiographs instead of the (reconstructed) image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] New methods suggest the use of multi-dimensional, fuzzy rule-based, non-linear thresholds.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In these approaches, the decision regarding each pixel's membership in a segment is based on multi-dimensional rules derived from fuzzy logic and evolutionary algorithms, considering factors such as image lighting, environment, and application.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Note that a common technique to improve performance for large images is to downsample the image, compute the clusters, and then reassign the values to the larger image if necessary.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The K-means algorithm is an iterative technique that is used to partition an image into *K* clusters.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In this case, distance is the squared or absolute difference between a pixel and a cluster center.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The difference is typically based on pixel color, intensity, texture, and location, or a weighted combination of these factors.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] *K* can be selected manually, randomly, or by a heuristic.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This algorithm is guaranteed to converge, but it may not return the optimal solution.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The quality of the solution depends on the initial set of clusters and the value of *K*.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The Mean Shift algorithm is a technique that is used to partition an image into an unknown apriori number of clusters.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This has the advantage of not having to start with an initial guess of such parameter which makes it a better general solution for more diverse cases.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Motion based segmentation is a technique that relies on motion in the image to perform segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The idea is simple: look at the differences between a pair of images.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Assuming the object of interest is moving, the difference will be exactly that object.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Improving on this idea, Kenney et al. proposed interactive segmentation [2].
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] They use a robot to poke objects in order to generate the motion signal necessary for motion-based segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Interactive segmentation follows the interactive perception framework proposed by Dov Katz [3] and Oliver Brock [4].
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Another technique that is based on motion is rigid motion segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Compression based methods postulate that the optimal segmentation is the one that minimizes, over all possible segmentations, the coding length of the data.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The connection between these two concepts is that segmentation tries to find patterns in an image and any regularity in the image can be used to compress it.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The method describes each segment by its texture and boundary shape.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Texture is encoded by lossy compression in a way similar to minimum description length (MDL) principle, but here the length of the data given the model is approximated by the number of samples times the entropy of the model.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The texture in each region is modeled by a multivariate normal distribution whose entropy has a closed form expression.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] An interesting property of this model is that the estimated entropy bounds the true entropy of the data from above.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This is because among all distributions with a given mean and covariance, normal distribution has the largest entropy.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Thus, the true coding length cannot be more than what the algorithm tries to minimize.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] For any given segmentation of an image, this scheme yields the number of bits required to encode that image based on the given segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Thus, among all possible segmentations of an image, the goal is to find the segmentation which produces the shortest coding length.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This can be achieved by a simple agglomerative clustering method.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The distortion in the lossy compression determines the coarseness of the segmentation and its optimal value may differ for each image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This parameter can be estimated heuristically from the contrast of textures in an image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] For example, when the textures in an image are similar, such as in camouflage images, stronger sensitivity and thus lower quantization is required.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Histogram-based methods are very efficient compared to other image segmentation methods because they typically require only one pass through the pixels.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In this technique, a histogram is computed from all of the pixels in the image, and the peaks and valleys in the histogram are used to locate the clusters in the image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Color or intensity can be used as the measure.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A refinement of this technique is to recursively apply the histogram-seeking method to clusters in the image in order to divide them into smaller clusters.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This operation is repeated with smaller and smaller clusters until no more clusters are formed.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] One disadvantage of the histogram-seeking method is that it may be difficult to identify significant peaks and valleys in the image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Histogram-based approaches can also be quickly adapted to apply to multiple frames, while maintaining their single pass efficiency.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The histogram can be done in multiple fashions when multiple frames are considered.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The same approach that is taken with one frame can be applied to multiple, and after the results are merged, peaks and valleys that were previously difficult to identify are more likely to be distinguishable.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The histogram can also be applied on a per-pixel basis where the resulting information is used to determine the most frequent color for the pixel location.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This approach segments based on active objects and a static environment, resulting in a different type of segmentation useful in video tracking.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Edge detection is a well-developed field on its own within image processing.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Region boundaries and edges are closely related, since there is often a sharp adjustment in intensity at the region boundaries.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Edge detection techniques have therefore been used as the base of another segmentation technique.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The edges identified by edge detection are often disconnected.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] To segment an object from an image however, one needs closed region boundaries.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The desired edges are the boundaries between such objects or spatial-taxons.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Spatial-taxons are information granules, consisting of a crisp pixel region, stationed at abstraction levels within a hierarchical nested scene architecture.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] They are similar to the Gestalt psychological designation of figure-ground, but are extended to include foreground, object groups, objects and salient object parts.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Edge detection methods can be applied to the spatial-taxon region, in the same manner they would be applied to a silhouette.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Segmentation methods can also be applied to edges obtained from edge detectors.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The detection of isolated points in an image is a fundamental part of image segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This process primarily depends on the second derivative, indicating the use of the Laplacian operator.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The Laplacian operator is employed such that the partial derivatives are derived from a specific equation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This mathematical expression can be implemented by convolving with an appropriate mask.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] If we extend this equation to three dimensions (x,y,z), the intensity at each pixel location around a central pixel at (x, y, z) is replaced by their corresponding values.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This equation becomes particularly useful when we assume that all pixels have unit spacing along each axis.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A sphere mask has been developed for use with three-dimensional datasets.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The sphere mask is designed to use only integer arithmetic during calculations, thereby eliminating the need for floating-point hardware or software.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] When applying these concepts to actual images represented as arrays of numbers, we need to consider what happens when we reach an edge or border region.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This above equation is used to determine whether a point in the image is an isolated point based on the response magnitude $|R(x,y)|$ and a threshold value T .
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] If the response magnitude is greater than or equal to the threshold, the function returns 1, indicating the presence of an isolated point; otherwise, it returns 0.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This helps in the effective detection and segmentation of isolated points in the image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The detection of isolated points has significant applications in various fields, including X-ray image processing.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] For instance, an original X-ray image of a turbine blade can be examined pixel-by-pixel to detect porosity in the upper-right quadrant of the blade.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The result of applying an edge detector's response to this X-ray image can be approximated.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This demonstrates the segmentation of isolated points in an image with the aid of single-pixel probes.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This method is a combination of three characteristics of the image: partition of the image based on histogram analysis is checked by high compactness of the clusters (objects), and high gradients of their borders.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] For that purpose two spaces have to be introduced: one space is the one-dimensional histogram of brightness *H* = *H*(*B*); the second space is the dual 3-dimensional space of the original image itself *B* = *B*(*x*, *y*).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The first space allows to measure how compactly the brightness of the image is distributed by calculating a minimal clustering kmin.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The bitmap *b* is an object in dual space.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] On that bitmap a measure has to be defined reflecting how compact distributed black (or white) pixels are.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] So, the goal is to find objects with good borders.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] For all *T* the measure *M*DC = *G*/(*k* × *L*) has to be calculated (where *k* is difference in brightness between the object and the background, *L* is length of all borders, and *G* is mean gradient on the borders).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Maximum of MDC defines the segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Region-growing methods rely mainly on the assumption that the neighboring pixels within one region have similar values.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The common procedure is to compare one pixel with its neighbors.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] If a similarity criterion is satisfied, the pixel can be set to belong to the same cluster as one or more of its neighbors.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The selection of the similarity criterion is significant and the results are influenced by noise in all instances.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The method of Statistical Region Merging (SRM) starts by building the graph of pixels using 4-connectedness with edges weighted by the absolute value of the intensity difference.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Initially each pixel forms a single pixel region.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] SRM then sorts those edges in a priority queue and decides whether or not to merge the current regions belonging to the edge pixels using a statistical predicate.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] One region-growing method is the seeded region growing method.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This method takes a set of seeds as input along with the image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The seeds mark each of the objects to be segmented.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The regions are iteratively grown by comparison of all unallocated neighboring pixels to the regions.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The difference between a pixel's intensity value and the region's mean, $\delta$ , is used as a measure of similarity.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The pixel with the smallest difference measured in this way is assigned to the respective region.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This process continues until all pixels are assigned to a region.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Because seeded region growing requires seeds as additional input, the segmentation results are dependent on the choice of seeds, and noise in the image can cause the seeds to be poorly placed.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Another region-growing method is the unseeded region growing method.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] It is a modified algorithm that does not require explicit seeds.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] It starts with a single region $A_{1}$ —the pixel chosen here does not markedly influence the final segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] At each iteration it considers the neighboring pixels in the same way as seeded region growing.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] It differs from seeded region growing in that if the minimum $\delta$ is less than a predefined threshold T then it is added to the respective region $A_{j}$ .
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] If not, then the pixel is considered different from all current regions $A_{i}$ and a new region $A_{n+1}$ is created with this pixel.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] One variant of this technique, proposed by Haralick and Shapiro (1985), is based on pixel intensities.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The mean and scatter of the region and the intensity of the candidate pixel are used to compute a test statistic.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] If the test statistic is sufficiently small, the pixel is added to the region, and the region's mean and scatter are recomputed.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Otherwise, the pixel is rejected, and is used to form a new region.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A special region-growing method is called $\lambda$ -connected segmentation (see also lambda-connectedness).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] It is based on pixel intensities and neighborhood-linking paths.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A degree of connectivity (connectedness) is calculated based on a path that is formed by pixels.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] For a certain value of $\lambda$ , two pixels are called $\lambda$ -connected if there is a path linking those two pixels and the connectedness of this path is at least $\lambda$ . $\lambda$ -connectedness is an equivalence relation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Split-and-merge segmentation is based on a quadtree partition of an image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] It is sometimes called quadtree segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This method starts at the root of the tree that represents the whole image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] If it is found non-uniform (not homogeneous), then it is split into four child squares (the splitting process), and so on.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] If, in contrast, four child squares are homogeneous, they are merged as several connected components (the merging process).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The node in the tree is a segmented node.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This process continues recursively until no further splits or merges are possible.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] When a special data structure is involved in the implementation of the algorithm of the method, its time complexity can reach $O(n\log n)$ , an optimal algorithm of the method.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Using a partial differential equation (PDE)-based method and solving the PDE equation by a numerical scheme, one can segment the image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Curve propagation is a popular technique in this category, with numerous applications to object extraction, object tracking, stereo reconstruction, etc.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The central idea is to evolve an initial curve towards the lowest potential of a cost function, where its definition reflects the task to be addressed.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] As for most inverse problems, the minimization of the cost functional is non-trivial and imposes certain smoothness constraints on the solution, which in the present case can be expressed as geometrical constraints on the evolving curve.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Lagrangian techniques are based on parameterizing the contour according to some sampling strategy and then evolving each element according to image and internal terms.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Nowadays, efficient "discretized" formulations have been developed to address these limitations while maintaining high efficiency.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In both cases, energy minimization is generally conducted using a steepest-gradient descent, whereby derivatives are computed using, e.g., finite differences.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The level-set method was initially proposed to track moving interfaces by Dervieux and Thomasset in 1979 and 1981 and was later reinvented by Osher and Sethian in 1988.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This has spread across various imaging domains in the late 1990s.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] It can be used to efficiently address the problem of curve/surface/etc. propagation in an implicit manner.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The central idea is to represent the evolving contour using a signed function whose zero corresponds to the actual contour.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Then, according to the motion equation of the contour, one can easily derive a similar flow for the implicit surface that when applied to the zero level will reflect the propagation of the contour.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The level-set method affords numerous advantages: it is implicit, is parameter-free, provides a direct way to estimate the geometric properties of the evolving structure, allows for change of topology, and is intrinsic.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] It can be used to define an optimization framework, as proposed by Zhao, Merriman and Osher in 1996.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] One can conclude that it is a very convenient framework for addressing numerous applications of computer vision and medical image analysis.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Research into various level-set data structures has led to very efficient implementations of this method.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The fast marching method has been used in image segmentation, and this model has been improved (permitting both positive and negative propagation speeds) in an approach called the generalized fast marching method.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The goal of variational methods is to find a segmentation which is optimal with respect to a specific energy functional.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The functionals consist of a data fitting term and a regularizing terms.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A minimizer $u^{*}$ is a piecewise constant image which has an optimal tradeoff between the squared L2 distance to the given image f and the total length of its jump set.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The jump set of $u^{*}$ defines a segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The relative weight of the energies is tuned by the parameter $\gamma >0$ .
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The binary variant of the Potts model, i.e., if the range of u is restricted to two values, is often called Chan-Vese model.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The functional value is the sum of the total length of the segmentation curve K , the smoothness of the approximation u , and its distance to the original image f .
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The weight of the smoothness penalty is adjusted by $\mu >0$ .
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The Potts model is often called piecewise constant Mumford-Shah model as it can be seen as the degenerate case $\mu \to \infty$ .
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The optimization problems are known to be NP-hard in general but near-minimizing strategies work well in practice.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Classical algorithms are graduated non-convexity and Ambrosio-Tortorelli approximation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Graph partitioning methods are an effective tools for image segmentation since they model the impact of pixel neighborhoods on a given cluster of pixels or pixel, under the assumption of homogeneity in images.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In these methods, the image is modeled as a weighted, undirected graph.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Usually a pixel or a group of pixels are associated with nodes and edge weights define the (dis)similarity between the neighborhood pixels.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The graph (image) is then partitioned according to a criterion designed to model "good" clusters.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Each partition of the nodes (pixels) output from these algorithms are considered an object segment in the image; see Segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Some popular algorithms of this category are normalized cuts, random walker, minimum cut, isoperimetric partitioning, minimum spanning tree-based segmentation, and segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The application of Markov random fields (MRF) for images was suggested in early 1984 by Geman and Geman.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Their strong mathematical foundation and ability to provide a global optimum even when defined on local features proved to be the foundation for novel research in the domain of image analysis, de-noising and segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] MRFs are completely characterized by their prior probability distributions, marginal probability distributions, cliques, smoothing constraint as well as criterion for updating values.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The criterion for image segmentation using MRFs is restated as finding the labelling scheme which has maximum probability for a given set of features.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The broad categories of image segmentation using MRFs are supervised and unsupervised segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In terms of image segmentation, the function that MRFs seek to maximize is the probability of identifying a labelling scheme given a particular set of features are detected in the image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] This is a restatement of the maximum a posteriori estimation method.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] 3. where *fi* ∈ Σ is the set containing features extracted for pixel i and define an initial set of clusters.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Using the training data compute the mean (*μ**ℓ**i*) and variance (σ*ℓ**i*) for each label.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Compute the marginal distribution for the given labeling scheme *P*(*fi* | *ℓ**i*) using Bayes' theorem and the class statistics calculated earlier.
