[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The calculations can be implemented in log likelihood terms as well.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Each optimization algorithm is an adaptation of models from a variety of fields and they are set apart by their unique cost functions.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The common trait of cost functions is to penalize change in pixel value as well as difference in pixel label when compared to labels of neighboring pixels.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] where α is the penalty for change in pixel label and β is the penalty for difference in label between neighboring pixels and chosen pixel.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Here $N(i)$ is neighborhood of pixel i and δ is the Kronecker delta function.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A major issue with ICM is that, similar to gradient descent, it has a tendency to rest over local maxima and thus not obtain a globally optimal labeling scheme.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Derived as an analogue of annealing in metallurgy, simulated annealing (SA) uses change in pixel label over iterations and estimates the difference in energy of each newly formed graph to the initial data.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] the algorithm selects the newly formed graph.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Simulated annealing requires the input of temperature schedules which directly affects the speed of convergence of the system, as well as energy threshold for minimization to occur.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A range of other methods exist for solving simple as well as higher order MRFs.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] They include Maximization of Posterior Marginal, Multi-scale MAP estimation, Multiple Resolution segmentation and more.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Apart from likelihood estimates, graph-cut using maximum flow and other highly constrained graph based methods exist for solving MRFs.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The expectation–maximization algorithm is utilized to iteratively estimate the a posterior probabilities and distributions of labeling when no training data is available and no estimate of segmentation model can be formed.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] E step: Estimate class statistics based on the random segmentation model defined.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Using these, compute the conditional probability of belonging to a label given the feature set is calculated using naive Bayes' theorem.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Here $\lambda \in \Lambda$ , the set of all possible labels.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] M step: The established relevance of a given feature set to a labeling scheme is now used to compute the a priori estimate of a given label in the second part of the algorithm.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Since the actual number of total labels is unknown (from a training data set), a hidden estimate of the number of labels given by the user is utilized in computations.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] where $\Omega$ is the set of all possible features.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Approximate MAP estimates are computationally expensive to calculate.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Extension to multi-class labeling degrades performance and increases storage required.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Reliable estimation of parameters for EM is required for global optima to be achieved.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Based on method of optimization, segmentation may cluster to local minima.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The watershed transformation considers the gradient magnitude of an image as a topographic surface.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Pixels having the highest gradient magnitude intensities (GMIs) correspond to watershed lines, which represent the region boundaries.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Water placed on any pixel enclosed by a common watershed line flows downhill to a common local intensity minimum (LIM).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Pixels draining to a common minimum form a catch basin, which represents a segment.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The central assumption of model-based approaches is that the structures of interest have a tendency towards a particular shape.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Therefore, one can seek a probabilistic model that characterizes the shape and its variation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] When segmenting an image, constraints can be imposed using this model as a prior.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Such a task may involve (i) registration of the training examples to a common pose, (ii) probabilistic representation of the variation of the registered samples, and (iii) statistical inference between the model and the image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Other important methods in the literature for model-based segmentation include active shape models and active appearance models.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Image segmentations are computed at multiple scales in scale space and sometimes propagated from coarse to fine scales; see scale-space segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Segmentation criteria can be arbitrarily complex and may take into account global as well as local criteria.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A common requirement is that each region must be connected in some sense.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Witkin's seminal work in scale space included the notion that a one-dimensional signal could be unambiguously segmented into regions, with one scale parameter controlling the scale of segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A key observation is that the zero-crossings of the second derivatives (minima and maxima of the first derivative or slope) of multi-scale-smoothed versions of a signal form a nesting tree, which defines hierarchical relations between segments at different scales.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Specifically, slope extrema at coarse scales can be traced back to corresponding features at fine scales.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] When a slope maximum and slope minimum annihilate each other at a larger scale, the three segments that they separated merge into one segment, thus defining the hierarchy of segments.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] There have been numerous research works in this area, out of which a few have now reached a state where they can be applied either with interactive manual intervention (usually with application to medical imaging) or fully automatically.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The following is a brief overview of some of the main research ideas that current approaches are based upon.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The nesting structure that Witkin described is, however, specific for one-dimensional signals and does not trivially transfer to higher-dimensional images.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Nevertheless, this general idea has inspired several other authors to investigate coarse-to-fine schemes for image segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Koenderink proposed to study how iso-intensity contours evolve over scales and this approach was investigated in more detail by Lifshitz and Pizer.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Unfortunately, however, the intensity of image features changes over scales, which implies that it is hard to trace coarse-scale image features to finer scales using iso-intensity information.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Bergholm proposed to detect edges at coarse scales in scale-space and then trace them back to finer scales with manual choice of both the coarse detection scale and the fine localization scale.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Gauch and Pizer studied the complementary problem of ridges and valleys at multiple scales and developed a tool for interactive image segmentation based on multi-scale watersheds.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The use of multi-scale watershed with application to the gradient map has also been investigated by Olsen and Nielsen and been carried over to clinical use by Dam.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Vincken et al. proposed a hyperstack for defining probabilistic relations between image structures at different scales.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The use of stable image structures over scales has been furthered by Ahuja and his co-workers into a fully automated system.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A fully automatic brain segmentation algorithm based on closely related ideas of multi-scale watersheds has been presented by Undeman and Lindeberg and been extensively tested in brain databases.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] These ideas for multi-scale image segmentation by linking image structures over scales have also been picked up by Florack and Kuijper.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Bijaoui and Rué associate structures detected in scale-space above a minimum noise threshold into an object tree which spans multiple scales and corresponds to a kind of feature in the original signal.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Extracted features are accurately reconstructed using an iterative conjugate gradient matrix method.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In one kind of segmentation, the user outlines the region of interest with the mouse clicks and algorithms are applied so that the path that best fits the edge of the image is shown.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Techniques like SIOX, Livewire, Intelligent Scissors or IT-SNAPS are used in this kind of segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In an alternative kind of semi-automatic segmentation, the algorithms return a spatial-taxon (i.e. foreground, object-group, object or object-part) selected by the user or designated via prior probabilities.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Most of the aforementioned segmentation methods are based only on color information of pixels in the image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Humans use much more knowledge when performing image segmentation, but implementing this knowledge would cost considerable human engineering and computational time, and would require a huge domain knowledge database which does not currently exist.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Trainable segmentation methods, such as neural network segmentation, overcome these issues by modeling the domain knowledge from a dataset of labeled pixels.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] An image segmentation neural network can process small areas of an image to extract simple features such as edges.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Another neural network, or any decision-making mechanism, can then combine these features to label the areas of an image accordingly.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A type of network designed this way is the Kohonen map.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Pulse-coupled neural networks (PCNNs) are neural models proposed by modeling a cat's visual cortex and developed for high-performance biomimetic image processing.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In 1989, Reinhard Eckhorn introduced a neural model to emulate the mechanism of a cat's visual cortex.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The Eckhorn model provided a simple and effective tool for studying the visual cortex of small mammals, and was soon recognized as having significant application potential in image processing.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In 1994, the Eckhorn model was adapted to be an image processing algorithm by John L.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Johnson, who termed this algorithm Pulse-Coupled Neural Network.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Over the past decade, PCNNs have been utilized for a variety of image processing applications, including: image segmentation, feature generation, face extraction, motion detection, region growing, noise reduction, and so on.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] A PCNN is a two-dimensional neural network.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Each neuron in the network corresponds to one pixel in an input image, receiving its corresponding pixel's color information (e.g. intensity) as an external stimulus.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Each neuron also connects with its neighboring neurons, receiving local stimuli from them.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The external and local stimuli are combined in an internal activation system, which accumulates the stimuli until it exceeds a dynamic threshold, resulting in a pulse output.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Through iterative computation, PCNN neurons produce temporal series of pulse outputs.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The temporal series of pulse outputs contain information of input images and can be utilized for various image processing applications, such as image segmentation and feature generation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Compared with conventional image processing means, PCNNs have several significant merits, including robustness against noise, independence of geometric variations in input patterns, capability of bridging minor intensity variations in input patterns, etc.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] In 2015, convolutional neural networks reached state of the art in semantic segmentation.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] U-Net is an architecture which takes as input an image and outputs a label for each pixel.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] U-Net initially was developed to detect cell boundaries in biomedical images.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] U-Net follows classical autoencoder architecture, as such it contains two sub-structures.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The encoder structure follows the traditional stack of convolutional and max pooling layers to increase the receptive field as it goes through the layers.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] It is used to capture the context in the image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The decoder structure utilizes transposed convolution layers for upsampling so that the end dimensions are close to that of the input image.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Skip connections are placed between convolution and transposed convolution layers of the same shape in order to preserve details that would have been lost otherwise.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Related images such as a photo album or a sequence of video frames often contain semantically similar objects and scenes, therefore it is often beneficial to exploit such correlations.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] The task of simultaneously segmenting scenes from related images or video frames is termed co-segmentation, which is typically used in human action localization.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Unlike conventional bounding box-based object detection, human action localization methods provide finer-grained results, typically per-image segmentation masks delineating the human object of interest and its action category (e.g., *Segment-Tube*).
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] Techniques such as dynamic Markov Networks, CNN and LSTM are often employed to exploit the inter-frame correlations.
[src:scikit-image/image-segmentation] There are many other methods of segmentation like multispectral segmentation or connectivity-based segmentation based on DTI images.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] Topological and geometrical continuous-space concepts such as size, shape, convexity, connectivity, and geodesic distance, were introduced by MM on both continuous and discrete spaces.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] MM is also the foundation of morphological image processing, which consists of a set of operators that transform images according to the above characterizations.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] The basic morphological operators are erosion, dilation, opening and closing.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] MM was originally developed for binary images, and was later extended to grayscale functions and images.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] The subsequent generalization to complete lattices is widely accepted today as MM's theoretical foundation.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] Mathematical Morphology was developed in 1964 by the collaborative work of Georges Matheron and Jean Serra, at the *École des Mines de Paris*, France.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] Matheron supervised the PhD thesis of Serra, devoted to the quantification of mineral characteristics from thin cross sections, and this work resulted in a novel practical approach, as well as theoretical advancements in integral geometry and topology.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] In 1968, the *Centre de Morphologie Mathématique* was founded by the École des Mines de Paris in Fontainebleau, France, led by Matheron and Serra.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] A random approach was also developed, based on novel image models.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] Most of the work in that period was developed in Fontainebleau.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] From the mid-1970s to mid-1980s, MM was generalized to grayscale functions and images as well.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] Besides extending the main concepts (such as dilation, erosion, etc.) to functions, this generalization yielded new operators, such as morphological gradients, top-hat transform and the Watershed (MM's main segmentation approach).
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] In the 1980s and 1990s, MM gained a wider recognition, as research centers in several countries began to adopt and investigate the method.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] MM started to be applied to a large number of imaging problems and applications, especially in the field of non-linear filtering of noisy images.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] In 1986, Serra further generalized MM, this time to a theoretical framework based on complete lattices.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] This generalization brought flexibility to the theory, enabling its application to a much larger number of structures, including color images, video, graphs, meshes, etc.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] At the same time, Matheron and Serra also formulated a theory for morphological filtering, based on the new lattice framework.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] The 1990s and 2000s also saw further theoretical advancements, including the concepts of *connections* and *levelings*.
[src:scikit-image/mathematical-morphology] In 1993, the first International Symposium on Mathematical Morphology (ISMM) took place in Barcelona, Spain.
[src:scikit-image/page] Welcome! scikit-image is an image processing toolbox which builds on numpy, scipy.ndimage and other libraries to provide a versatile set of image processing routines in Python.
